<subSubSection box="[151,436,690,715]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,690,931]" box="[151,436,690,715]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Holotype female in CAS.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="516" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,690,931]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,726,751]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Postsutural dorsocentrals 3; postsutural transverse band extending medially as a brown vitta reaching scutellum; mid femur with one median anterior seta and 2 posterior preapicals; mid tibia with two posterior setae on middle third.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,690,931]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,834,859]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Notes.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[539,637,834,859]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">holotype</typeStatus>
female. Ovipositor and spermatheca illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Couri" box="[1223,1433,834,859]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" refString="Couri, M. S., Pont, A. C. &amp; Penny, N. D. (2006) Muscidae (Diptera) from Madagascar: identification keys, descriptions of new species, and new records. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 57, 799 - 923." type="journal article" year="2006">
Couri 
<emphasis box="[1296,1346,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">et al</emphasis>
. (2006
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[151,234,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 89 – 103" captionStartId="25.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[190,1408,221,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[179,1408,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 89 – 103. Sternite 5; cercal plate and surstyli in dorsal view (not figured for L. quadristriata); epandrium, cercal plate and surstyli in lateral view; aedeagus in lateral view: 89 – 91. Limnophora quadristriata Emden. 92 – 95. Limnophora sinuosa sp. nov. 96 – 99. Limnophora somereni Emden. 100 – 103. Limnophora spinata Stein." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242403/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
). The species runs to couplet 38 and to 
<taxonomicName box="[672,819,870,894]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perfidodes">
<emphasis box="[672,819,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">L. perfidodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of Emden’s key. 
<bibRefCitation box="[1013,1220,870,895]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" refString="Couri, M. S., Pont, A. C. &amp; Penny, N. D. (2006) Muscidae (Diptera) from Madagascar: identification keys, descriptions of new species, and new records. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 57, 799 - 923." type="journal article">
Couri 
<emphasis box="[1083,1139,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">et al.</emphasis>
(2006)
</bibRefCitation>
gave the following key to separate the two species:
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="516" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<key pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,978,1117]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
1. Arista with short hairs, shorter than the width of postpedicel; calypter yellow; cell r5 at wing tip more than twice as wide as length of cross-vein 
<emphasis box="[421,455,1008,1029]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">r-m</emphasis>
; pale dust on abdomen between and outside the black brown spots, the spots therefore indistinct.............................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName box="[1297,1436,1037,1058]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesovittata">
<emphasis box="[1297,1436,1037,1058]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">L. mesovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,978,1117]" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
<keyLead pageId="15" pageNumber="516">
- Arista with the longest hairs equal to the width of postpedicel; calypter creamy; cell r5 at wing tip about twice as wide as length of cross-vein 
<emphasis box="[421,455,1096,1117]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">r-m</emphasis>
; pale dust on abdomen grey, the black spots very distinct and well defined........... 
<taxonomicName box="[1309,1435,1095,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Limnophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="516" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perfidodes">
<emphasis box="[1309,1435,1095,1117]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="516">L. perfidodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</key>
</keyStep>
